":"1220–1275","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1235–1275":"1235–1275","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1195–Female":"1195–Deceased","1190":"1190","before 1235":"before 1235","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1220":"1220","about 1235":"about 1235","1275":"1275","1195":"1195","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England":"Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Boothe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Booth  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Booth","meanings":["English (northern): topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>bothe</i> (Old Danish <i>bōth</i>) ‘temporary shelter, such as a covered market stall or a cattle-herdsman's hut’. The latter sense was predominant in the Pennines of Lancashire and Yorkshire, where there were many cattle farms or vaccaries, and whose subdivisions were known as ‘booths’. The principal meaning of the surname there was therefore probably ‘cattle herdsman’, ‘man in charge of a vaccary’, and thus identical with   Boothman  . Elsewhere it may have denoted a shopkeeper who owned a temporary market stall, but no evidence has been found to confirm this use of the surname. In the British Isles the surname is still more common in northern England, where Scandinavian influence was more marked, and in Scotland, where the word was borrowed into Gaelic as <i>both(an)</i>.","History: Robert Booth (1604–72) is mentioned in the colonial records of Exeter, NH, in 1645. He subsequently moved to ME."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam de Boothe was born in 1220, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, his father, Adam de Booth, was 31 and his mother, Mrs Adam de Booth, was 25. He married Mrs Adam de Boothe of Cheshire before 1235. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1275, in Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1220–1275":"1220–1275","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1235–1275":"1235–1275","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1190":"1190","before 1235":"enne 1235","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1220":"1220","about 1235":"umbes 1235","1275":"1275","1195":"1195","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England":"Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1220–1275":"1220–1275","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1235–1275":"1235–1275","1190–Male":"1190–Kuol